"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-08-chinese-hockey-player-slammed-endangering-opponent-olympics-21383340\", \"text\": \"A Chinese hockey player was slammed for 'endangering' an opponent during theOlympicsemi-final inParis.  Chinaproduced a big upset to stun Belgium at the Yves-du-Manoir Stadium and book their place in the women's field hockey final.  The clash finished 1-1 in regulation time and China won a tense penalty shootout 3-2 as they look to claim their first medal in this event since 2008.  There was drama when the full-time whistle was blown as Chinese midfielder Fan Yunxia smashed the ball out of frustration into Delphine-Daphne Marien, causing the Belgian forward to drop to the floor and wince in pain.  Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for updates from the Paris 2024 Olympics  The Belgium players and coaching staff were understandably furious, with many angrily approaching Fan, forcing the officials to intervene as boos rang out from the crowd.  Once order was restored the referee showed yellow cards to both Fan and Judith Vandermeiren - who appeared to shove the Chinese star during the melee.  'There is the final whistle and oh, that's unnecessary from Fan,' the Eurosport commentator said. 'She's just hammered the ball and hit one of the Belgium players.  A Chinese hockey player smashed the ball into a Belgian player after the whistle at the Olympics \\u00f0\\u009f\\u008f\\u0091\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0092\\u00a5Just listen to the boos \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0098\\u00ac#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/w4zl184KQ4  'Everyone is coming out onto the pitch. That was reckless and dangerous, I think it was frustration more than anything else. I am sure she did not mean to hit the player but she's rifled it straight at her.'  Speaking to Fan via a translator, the referee said: 'The player has hit the ball after the whistle and that is dangerous so it's a yellow card.'  When the translator tried to protest the referee added: 'It's dangerous and she cannot do it.'  Explaining why Belgium's Vandermeiren also received a yellow card, the referee said: 'Number seven, it's a yellow card because you have come in and shoved an opponent. You cannot do that.'  China face formidable Netherlands in the Paris 2024 Olympic final. The Dutch side are bidding to defend the title they won in Tokyo in their sixth successive final.  'We did what we had to do,' China coach Alyson Annan said. 'These games you need to win. It does not have to be pretty.  'We have also practiced shootouts every single training for the last year and a half. Every training. We did not miss a training. That paid off tonight.  'You cannot leave anything out on the field. You have to give it your all. They did that. We are in the final.'  Belgium, meanwhile, now turn their attentions to a bronze medal match against Argentina.  'It's a tough one to take. I think we were very close today,' Vandermeiren said. 'The pride of making it this far will definitely come later.  'At this point, it's a disappointment to be this close to an Olympic final because that's not something that happens a lot in a lifetime.  'We have not been to the Olympics for 12 years. If you can play for a medal, you should not hesitate for a second.  'Even though we wanted to play in the final, we can still get the first medal in the history of Belgium Hockey, so we should go for it.'  For more stories like this,check our sport page.  Follow Metro Sport for the latest news onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram.  ArrowMORE:Olympian opens up about 'terrible mistake' after Paris drugs arrest  ArrowMORE:Games Inbox: The PS5 becoming a flop, PS6 vs. PS5 Pro, and Nintendo Switch 2 sequels  ArrowMORE:Quincy Hall's family react to his incredible comeback to seal Olympic gold over Matthew Hudson-Smith  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"